9:
...Heed me, spirits of water. Flowing
and formless, become frigid and
white.
13:
Emma. As I've said many times
before, you mustn't use your magic
on others.
18:
I think snow would look good on you,
so I thought I'd send some your way.
Aren't you happy?
21: Emma, listen. I like snow too, but—
28:
I'm afraid Emma's disruptions are
getting worse.
32:
Emma... Is she the one you're
bringing to the holiday party?
35:
She's my granddaughter.
I'm sorry, Reylas. It seems she's not
doing well during the holidays.
37:
...Her parents don't get along. 
I couldn't to see how it was affecting
her, so I had her come stay in a
dorm at the Academy.
39:
I don't want her to feel alone, but...
It's quite the troubled situation.
49: Hm... Yes, let's start from there.
52:
I can't say it will be everything she's
hoping for, but...
56:
Let's do everything we can to make
Emma's dream a reality.
63:
A ballroom dance! That's exactly
what you wanna go for!
67:
The intimate distance, the gentle
whispers... The warmth of each
other's hands... Eek!
72:
M-Meryll! You seem really familiar
with this!
76:
A ballroom dance, hm? It's been
quite some time since my last one...
Alk, would you care to dance?
84:
Yes. I can teach you how to lead
and to follow. It might prove to be
useful knowledge someday.
88:
I-I'm not planning on being in that
sort of situation for a while...
91:
Oh? I happen to know of a number
of partners who might be interested—
96:
Actually! I think some dance
practice would be PERFECT right
about now!
103:
Mom and dad aren't gonna start
being nice just because I wrote out
this dumb thing.
105:
I wish it would snow... I wish it would
pile up so much that I can't hear
everyone having fun out there.
109:
How about something to eat,
Emma? A visiting cook from the
Guild has made some pretty
delicious stuff.
111:
No thanks. And Gramps? You can go
now.
112:
You've got business to take care of
with people from the Guild, right?
Just leave me here.
115:
...There isn't anyone I'd rather be with
than you, Emma. I'll be with you until
Reylas arrives.
119:
It looks wonderful on you. 
Just as I thought it would.
121:
That's a poinsettia, you know. 
A symbol of blessings and good
fortune.
124:
...Don't make fun of me. 
I know that much.
133:
Would you care to spend this
evening together, my dear?
140:
All right. In any case, let's be off,
Emma.
144:
My friends are here, and I'd love for
you to meet them.
150:
Hey! Are we all having a good time
tonight?!
157:
Break the silence and let the world
shine! Freeze Ray Diamond Dust!
168:
What do you think of my friends,
Emma?
171:
Noisy. This doesn't suit the festive
mood at all.
173:
Haha, you're not wrong. 
But it's not lonely either, right?
176:
Now then, let's dance. I know a thing
or two about it, so just follow my
lead.
178: ...You better not step on my toes.
183:
Wow! That was awesome! I've never
spent the holidays like this before!
186:
But... Professor? You read my letter
to Santa, didn't you?
188:
Thanks for the pretty snow. It was
super noisy in there, though.
191:
But maybe a little noise isn't so bad
on a day like today. Much better
than being alone.
196:
...I understand that families often
struggle to understand one another.
I know that all too well.
204:
...There's so much more to the world
than you see now, Emma. There's
always somebody else out there
who can help you understand
something you can't right now.
207:
And that person doesn't have to be
one of your parents, or even a friend.
You can even learn from someone
you once considered an enemy.
210:
...One day, you'll find the answers
you're looking for. And until then,
we'll all be here by your side.
214:
Your grandfather. Your classmates...
Know that you aren't alone, Emma.
217:
Thank you, Professor. You... You're
my Santa this year.
220:
Is that so?
...I'm glad to hear that.
